More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important for a person’s healthy development is the environment in which he grows and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half as often on the table as in families where normal children live.
More than 19 percent of the overweight children had potatoes for dinner on the eve of the education campaign under the motto "obesity is not a coincidence".
In families with obesity, sport is not exactly one of their favorite occupations, however, as is also the majority of today’s students – only 15 percent answered that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, with nearly 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic being surveyed.
This was already the second year of the campaign "Obesity is not a coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Insurance Fund and the Unilever company.
So far, more than 12,000 students from 4th and 8th grades participated in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the horribly increasing number of overweight or even obese children.
"Only half of the children surveyed, for example, led to eating breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-veesper-dinner bread five times a day - one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet," says one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner bread
Experts point out that relatively small amounts, such as the family’s regular breakfast time, are also important for a child’s healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the students’ families have breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast on their own.
The worst thing was the finding that one in every 10 families is not breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered the basis of a healthy daily diet.
The survey showed, among other things, that in the families of overweight children, unhealthy potatoes are consumed much more often.
And almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet lemonades every day (70 percent)
While more than 40 percent of children surveyed do sports, only less than half of their parents do so – only 15 percent.
Set up your own menu
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to make their own meal plan out of the options offered, according to their appetite and opinion.
“What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in point diet is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite dishes were many flour dishes, meat dishes and, of course, sweet dishes.
"It is especially alarming the great popularity of sweet lemonades," the final report on this survey stresses.
At lunch, the main dish, teigwaren beat just before poultry.
The children almost did not like shellfish and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Back to Healthcare
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits when they get the right information.
"In the control group of respondents who completed the questionnaire after the conclusion of the clarifying lecture "Obesity is not a coincidence", there was in many cases a clear shift in preferences towards principles of healthy eating", is mentioned in the results of the project.
For example, this was the case with the sweet limos, where many children began to give preference to ordinary water.
In the questionnaire, the children also crossed much more often chicken or fish as the main dish of the day and were ready to eat less noodles or sweet food.
