Rezension
The initially careless ride becomes a complete avoidable, dilettante mistake for the routine ride to the early stages.
It was able to meet the ambitions for the most part, but what is the use of it if obviously no one wanted to do a little more.
Even before he came to the store, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
However, he promised to move the already aged game series "Need for Speed" to a new dimension again, and in the playable demonstration examples he did not seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious as to how the adapted passages came out, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and goes on foot.
But, as you’re used to with NFS, in the end, it’s a lot different than you expected.
Sure - potentially there are quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is shrunk by some superfluous mistakes that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So it's actually no longer a mistake, but rather a sign of an incomprehensible flaw of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
For the first time, one is introduced to the story, whose main character Jack has certain personal problems; the only solution seems to be to take part in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, so on the west coast, you get on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea includes a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race will take place on a different track and that the individual stages will take place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
You don’t have the impression that the game would offer the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are still clearly beautiful, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the previous parts of the series.
So nothing moving around the world.
But driving through the desert, through autumnal landscape or high through deep snowy landscape looks visually very pleasant.
From time to time, untypical elements bring a bit of variation into the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts vision.
In the mountains, you have to be careful not to be spoiled by a lavender.
At the same time, the individual races are built quite well behind each other.
Just a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overcome the required number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to pick up (classical race against the stopwatch), then wait for another personal duel with a single counterpart.
And that's what the police are doing, trying to fool one of them.
A novelty are the passages in which Jack leaves the car.
Rather, it’s about certain interactive animations where Jack runs away from someone and where the player needs to help him by pressing the right button at the right time.
So, nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer such passages in the game than you would expect (only three in particular).
Ultimately, this is more of an advantage, because this element has at least no chance of getting bored - it belongs to the elements that make the game more diverse in the context of the above mentioned.
The driving model walks in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today’s point of view, it doesn’t tear down trees, on the other hand, one could not claim that it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you need to look elsewhere.
But an action-packed race will continue to be fairly well suited to the local driving model, even though it could be found better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in good order.
Real problems only appear after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not entirely OK.
It is hardly expected from a game of this kind that it calculates complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea before any impact on an object, how the car behaves, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: In some places, you "strip" the other car, but in other, almost identical situations, you get into slippery slopes and turn wild pirouettes.
Or the carriage goes straight to rubbish.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn’t matter any more, it’s annoying every time.
The restarts are solved as follows: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then one throws the game back to the last stop of the track.
Only - in each race you have only five restarts.
Once you've exhausted it, everything goes from the front.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something fails, but you should not rely on them.
Sometimes, however, the restart doesn’t even help, as nothing else helps but to learn the critical section from the head.
It is unpleasant that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some curves need to be passed in a very specific way, otherwise you simply do not fit through.
In other places, you will always encounter "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you come first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see the counterpart passing by in front of a playful two-entry cars, but until you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to overdrive or brake them.
And it doesn’t matter when you get there, everything is designed so that this situation always comes close to your nose.
The counterparties have other advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always outdated by the same opponent in the same place and again here, regardless of the time.
The most insane is the end of the game on the long bridge, which happens in the opposite direction.
The counterparty has to get one out of here, obviously on the devil.
And when he’s in front of one, he naturally takes a view, so you drive your own car there a few times at first.
Clear - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting but this intention is so clear that it quickly misses the joy of the game.
And that’s a shame, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is generally quite entertaining and sometimes so action-laden that you almost no longer know where one of the heads are.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what "blame" is about it - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something quite different...
An unusual idea is also to change cars during the course of the race.
You should not overlook the petrol stations on the route, because right here you can change the car, although in most cases the car you just have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for urban areas, the strong American limousines for straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical rides, for example on the Serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the game history mode also goes to task mode (challenges) - i.e. the races in the individual locations that you know from the story.
Here there are not only medals, but also points of experience for your own profile, which is common to the tasks (challenges) and history.
To get to the higher level of the driver, different items must be unlocked: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is at the same time associated with the online autolog feature, which compares the results obtained, among other things, with those of other players, and also provides other collective features.
One of the other incomprehensible snipers is a situation in the last race of history.
This is where you can get into a subway tunnel (meineways) by car, where you can rest on the rails in the dark (meineways).
On the Tacho look figures between 150 and 200 km/h (meanways), but there comes at once a subway from the rear and drives an uncompromising scrap.
In our editorial, we will probably argue for a long time whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is not overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is quite appealing in most cases and here and there and even brilliant.
What’s even more annoying is that in some exciting moments the image recovery frequency slows down, and sometimes this is quite dramatic.
However, this is particularly true for accidents with a larger number of participants, where a continuous FPS is useless anyway.
The sound playback is ok and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to address as wide a scale as possible to a young audience, a soundtrack was created "from everyone something" - but who buys such a game because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The emotions are rather mixed.
If the game hadn’t been shrunk by the totally unnecessary mistakes mentioned, we would have been able to claim with the chest tone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that’s how the game seems unfinished.
It’s a great pleasure for you, but you should be prepared to face these mistakes with the power of airport headlights.
