IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to World Flies
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago and was originally called Computing Tabulation Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM only in 1924 - originally a trademark designation for a branch in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later IBM company was the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They had technologies such as the famous card clocks for recording the beginning and end of the work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also held the chairmanship of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired Thomas J. Watson, the head of the competition firm, to help him run the company.
This leader even put the founders of IBM in the shadows – based on Watson’s ideas to this day, the company’s invincible culture and identity.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name implies, started with the manufacture and distribution of all kinds of machines for the trade - from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four decades in which Watson led the company, he doubled his sales to <0x24>9 million and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so essential to the company that he was in the chair for forty years, only then he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM’s technicians and computers helped direct NASA’s flights to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 the famous man’s flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC, which defined the computer standard of the time, came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand bought the consultant part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business of high-value consulting and services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the concept of “Smart Planet”.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned so far, e.g. to improve the situation in traffic and urban administration.
In the trading sector, IBM recently launched the “Smart Commerce” platform to help traders lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
As early as 1932, IBM established a branch in then Czechoslovakia – as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern Europe headquarters is located in Prague and there is also a world-class research team that deals with the technology of voice recognition.
