Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in the then <0xC4><0x8C>SSR: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies were selling only travel to the socialist Eastern bloc countries, in the West they were allowed to choose only.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the DDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania on the Black Sea and to Hungary on the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when you were also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that even the citizens of the Eastern bloc (i.e. the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely within the socialist countries.
If a citizen of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSR, for example, wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter to do so, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Already at that time, the travel agencies also offered to travel to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or even stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good friends" in the travel agency.
Even so, the thing hadn't worked out for a long time.
The so-called currency statement - the condition for a trip to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
In fact, the Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible without currency statements to leverage the necessary financial means (western currency) for a trip to the West.
Therefore, the vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend homes and datches - a habit that continues to this day.
The harmonious revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While vacations in the DDR or Bulgaria were the measure of all things until 1989, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, of which one is no longer aware today, is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989 at all, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, the currency obligation was lifted in the neighbouring Western European countries, resulting in a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
For example, when traveling to Paris, Czech vacationers slept in the tent in the park, because who would have already had the money for accommodation in a hotel or in a pension.
A typical feature of travel abroad from the Czech Republic at the time was a luggage compartment packed with canned, beer and permanent wurst, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and, as a result, the average wages increased, which ended in another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, after 1997, travel agencies began to regularly prepare for charter flights, making air travel, thanks to the possibility of negotiating quantity discounts, incredibly cheaper compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already exchange-free payments with all the highly developed countries in the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-town" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand for the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers fly annually to distant sunny countries; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 Tsd. Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the era, which marked our “post-revolutionary” development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitively one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holiday abroad for the first time (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than CZK 15 tsd. per person for a single holiday.
