You are reading an excerpt from the interview, whose full copy can be found in the online edition of La Nación.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream comes true when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what that means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is the second time we have played in South and Central America, and so far it has been great.
I have only been to Costa Rica once for a holiday. It is such a beautiful country that we will definitely stay there for a few more days.
It is exciting for us to bring our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are completely committed, they experience the days before the concert more intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for being on our side all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we're sorry to have taken so long to get here.
Some people even think that your concert will become the biggest show of the year.
Doesn’t that put a little pressure on your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve done in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played on some giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play there.
We love this country, we love surfing and are passionate about the jungle, so Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always been to surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua. Together with Mexico are the excellent areas for surfing. In this way, about people who love surfing, we have learned about it.
With a look at the tour, you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played there, we don’t set limits.
We will try to give the best show possible with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
- Why?
I think that’s partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs, everyone likes a different song, so the decision we’re going to play isn’t easy.
If we put two or three songs that we no longer play in the repertoire, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked them, otherwise they could be forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I think that’s why it’s also for the audience.
With this tour, you will celebrate your twenty-year history.
If you look back, is it hard for you to believe in your success?
Yeah, total.
First of all, I think that none of us have ever imagined playing in a great rock band for over 20 years, which seems like a dream.
We also continue to rely on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like it and are excited to bring out music.
We are fortunate to be able to drive to the places of the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean for you to have been actively involved in the birth of the Grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of big bands.
We are good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and quite unusual when a movement comes out of a group of friends.
Occasionally, a band emerges from a city, but it is already unusual when five or ten groups come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We are still looking forward to being friends with them all and it is an honor to be part of this Seattle sound that came up.
It is also very unusual for a band like yours to have been together with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which alone is much more time than many bands last.
First of all, I believe that we all value being happy, still alive, and we take care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give each individual the freedom to experiment.
We can't get any better with each other and their music.
Your relationship with glory has not always been easy, but thanks to your success, you can always do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it’s too easy to drop this game with huge crowds of people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people came because of the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it has brought to life without relying on being a famous rock star.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and at first it was great.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
We were disappointed to have taken such a long time. We are still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who built the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I remember what an incredible man Andy was, and how he always brought me over to work and laughed and laughed. It was too much.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas is responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that’s why the band chose for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and we liked this band the most, which is why we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. That will certainly be exciting.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings him, and I think he sings the first thing that suits him.
Who was influenced by you as a bassist?
of so many<0x2B>
Among the first ones that come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk about the bassists I liked all afternoon.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fashion phenomenon?
I think we all don’t feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I like the bands I mentioned earlier, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others who came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think it’s great because it’s worth listening to this music and making bands like Mudhoney better than ever.
At first her music was darker, now she is more positive.
- Why?
This is interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a little light-hearted, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe, which are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive about themselves.
The tears came to both of them when I heard Ed play them. They're very dark songs.
I think when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life — for example, if you lose a family member or a friend — that affects your artistic creation and your music and these two songs clearly embodies that for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
