Fujimori to return to hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was taken to a public hospital on Tuesday to examine the muscle loss of his legs, his doctor said.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who spent 25 years in prison for human rights violations during his reign (1990-2000), has several diseases, including tongue cancer, which is operated on and under control four times.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a congressman and his personal doctor, told television that Fujimori would be examined at the Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplásicas in Peru for three days to determine the cause of his pain and muscle loss in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that, in his opinion, Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, yet he did not wish for this because he considered him innocent.
He was operated on four times on lung cancer and lost 18 kilograms of weight, including other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and problems with bleeding in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been in the National Directorate of Special Operations of the Police since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squadron of the Peruvian army, which served secretly during his reign.
