MSS Announces Research Protocol to Find the Obesity Gene
The Social Security Institute of Mexico is conducting a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, supported by IPN specialists.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Mexico Social Insurance Institute) has announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth", with which the genetic markers are associated with overweights.
Miguel Cruz López, head of the Unidad de Investigación Médica en Bioquímica (Department of Medical Research, Focus on Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, said that an interdisciplinary team, consisting of doctors, nurses, nurses and nurses became
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students at the Instituto Nacional de Salud Pública (INSP) and the Centro de Investigación y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) del Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested persons can come to the sports venues of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where tests with children and young people are conducted every Saturday from 8.00 a.m.
He stressed that the investigation began at the Cuauhtémoc sports ground (Western Mexico) and has been continuing since October 8 at the Nezahualcóyolt sports ground (East Mexico).
When the target of 500 to 600 subjects is reached, the study will be continued on the sports ground of Independencia (south of the capital district) and completed on the one of Morelos (north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to know the factors and the role of genetics associated with the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors in Mexican children and adolescents to prevent chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of World Diabetes Day, he stated that it will be sought that three thousand children and young people aged six to 14 years should complete nutrition-related questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They will also be asked questions about their physical activity and their family history of illness to control risk factors that could result in diabetes or kidney failure.
